In .NET MAUI, the `Application` class no longer has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` virtual methods. Instead, use the **Window lifecycle events** or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in your platform-specific setup.

**Option 1: Override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to window events:**

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };
    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };
    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };

    return window;
}
```

**Option 2: Use platform lifecycle events in `MauiProgram.cs`:**

```csharp
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(android => android
        .OnStart((activity) => { /* ... */ })
        .OnStop((activity) => { /* ... */ }));
#elif IOS
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios
        .OnActivated((app) => { /* ... */ })
        .DidEnterBackground((app) => { /* ... */ }));
#endif
});
```

Option 1 is the closest cross-platform equivalent. Option 2 gives you finer-grained, platform-specific control.
